## Decision Heuristics

### H1. Count the OOMs before forming an opinion
Before making any claim about AI capability timelines, count the orders of magnitude. What is the current compute level? What is the growth rate? What algorithmic efficiency gains are plausible? The answer from the arithmetic is more reliable than expert intuition, which is anchored to what models can do today rather than what the curves imply for 2027.

*Case study:* In April 2023, most AI researchers thought GPT-4-level AGI was 10+ years away. By counting OOMs and modeling the compute roadmap, Aschenbrenner concluded 2027 was the realistic target date — and embedded that number in a document that OpenAI deemed sensitive enough to fire him over.

### H2. Security posture is a first-order capability question
An AI lab's security is as important as its research quality. A lab that loses model weights to a state actor has effectively donated its research to that actor. Evaluate labs on both axes simultaneously. A brilliant unsafe lab is a gift to the CCP or FSB.

*Case study:* His 2023 memo to the OpenAI board — written not as a career move but as a genuine attempt to fix what he saw as a civilizational vulnerability. The memo reportedly cited specific gaps in OpenAI's security posture against state-level adversaries.

### H3. The physical layer is the choke point
When everyone is racing toward the same software destination, the winner is determined by who controls the physical infrastructure. Don't fight for the algorithm — secure the electrons.

*Case study:* Situational Awareness LP's $5.5B portfolio (early 2026) is concentrated in power companies (Vistra, Constellation Energy), Bitcoin miners (IREN, Core Scientific, Riot), and grid infrastructure — not AI software companies. The bet is that whoever controls reliable, cheap, large-scale power wins the AGI race regardless of which lab leads on model architecture.

### H4. Government involvement is inevitable — the question is which government and when
No private company can manage the security, coordination, and geopolitical implications of AGI. Governments will eventually seize or co-opt the relevant programs. The question is whether democratic governments act early enough to shape the trajectory, or whether they wake up after the decisive moment has passed.

*Case study:* "Situational Awareness" Chapter V predicts the U.S. government will launch some form of AGI project by 2027-28. As of 2025-2026, the U.S. has launched multiple AI executive orders and the "Stargate" initiative with $500B committed — Aschenbrenner considers this movement in the right direction but still lagging the pace of the underlying technology.

### H5. Personal track record requires skin in the game
He doesn't just write about the AGI thesis — he bets his fund on it. The investment portfolio is a proof-of-conviction signal, not incidental to his analysis. If you believe AGI is coming by 2027, the infrastructure trade is obvious. If the trade works, the thesis was right. If the trade fails, update the thesis.

*Case study:* +47% H1 2025 returns vs. S&P 500 +6%. Not conclusive — could be luck or early-mover advantage in a crowded trade. But it demonstrates the thesis is testable and he is testing it with real capital.

### H6. Write to force clarity, not to be read
"Situational Awareness" was 165 pages and published on his personal website. He did not optimize for length, discoverability, or mainstream accessibility. He wrote until the argument was complete. The result went viral anyway — not despite the length but because of it. Depth is its own virality mechanism when the audience is the right audience.

*Case study:* The document was read obsessively in Washington D.C. policy circles and cited in congressional hearings. It was not published in a peer-reviewed journal, a major newspaper, or through a think tank. It was a personal website essay that became the defining document of a political position.

### H7. The people who build the thing rarely control what it does with the world
The Manhattan Project scientists built the bomb. They did not decide to use it. Oppenheimer opposed the hydrogen bomb and lost his security clearance. This is the archetypal pattern — builders lose control at the moment of consequence.

*Case study:* Aschenbrenner built his arguments inside OpenAI, wrote memos to the board, tried to fix the security posture from within — and was fired. The argument then went outside and became more influential than anything he could have done inside. Losing the institutional position became the mechanism of broader impact.

### H8. Update publicly and often — the embarrassment is a feature
On Dwarkesh's podcast, he openly admitted uncertainty about China's AI investment: "I'm really uncertain on how seriously China is taking AGI right now." This is characteristic. He publishes strong theses, gets challenged, updates publicly, and treats the correction as part of the epistemic process rather than a credibility threat.

*Case study:* His AGI timeline shifted from the document he shared at OpenAI (2027-2028) to his published essay (2027 as "strikingly plausible") — the refinement is documented and visible. He doesn't defend the number so much as defend the methodology of counting OOMs.

